          "id": "te-l02-c1",
          "title": "Chapter 2",
          "content": "Chapter 2 - Second Lecture: The Expanding Universe\nOur sun, along with the twinkling stars we see at night, is part of a gigantic collection of stars known as the Milky Way galaxy. For many years, people believed that our galaxy was the entire universe. However, in 1924, an American astronomer named Edwin Hubble made a groundbreaking discovery: there are many other galaxies out there, each separated by vast stretches of empty space! This was a huge revelation because it changed how we understand our place in the cosmos.\nTo prove that there were other galaxies, Hubble needed to measure how far away these galaxies were from us. For nearby stars, we can easily determine their distance by observing how they shift position as the Earth orbits the sun. This method is called parallax, and it works well for stars that are relatively close to us. However, other galaxies are so far away that they appear fixed in the sky, making it impossible to use the same technique.\nTo tackle this challenge, Hubble had to use clever indirect methods to measure their distances. One of the key techniques he used involved observing the brightness of certain types of stars called Cepheid variables. These stars have a regular pattern of brightness that allows astronomers to determine how far away they are based on how bright they appear from Earth. By using these methods, Hubble was able to show that our Milky Way galaxy is just one of many galaxies in the universe, leading to the understanding that the universe is much larger and more complex than anyone had previously imagined. This discovery opened up a whole new understanding of the universe's size and structure, inspiring generations of scientists and astronomers to explore the cosmos further.\nContext recap: Chapter 2 - Second Lecture: The Expanding Universe\nOur sun, along with the twinkling stars we see at night, is part of a gigantic collection of stars known as the Milky Way galaxy. For many years, people believed that our galaxy was the entire universe. However, in 1924, an American astronomer named Edwin Hubble made a groundbreaking discovery: there are many other galaxies out there, each separated by vast stretches of empty space! This was a huge revelation because it changed how we understand our place in the cosmos.\nWhy this matters: Chapter 2 helps learners in Physics/Cosmology connect ideas from Illustrated Theory of Everything to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
