          "title": "Chapter 4",
          "content": "Chapter 4 - Fourth Lecture: Understanding Black Holes\nBefore the year 1970, my research was mainly about general relativity, which is a theory that explains how gravity works in our universe. I was particularly interested in whether there had been a big bang singularity, which is a point in time when the universe began. One evening, shortly after my daughter Lucy was born, I found myself thinking deeply about black holes as I got ready for bed. Because of my disability, this process took me a bit longer, which gave me plenty of time to reflect on these fascinating cosmic phenomena.\nAt that time, scientists had not yet come up with a clear definition of what points in space-time were considered to be inside a black hole and which were outside. This was an important question because understanding black holes is crucial to our knowledge of the universe. I had previously talked with my colleague Roger Penrose about how we might define a black hole. We came up with the idea that a black hole could be thought of as the set of events from which it is impossible to escape to a safe distance. This means that once something crosses the boundary of a black hole, it cannot return.\nThis definition has since become widely accepted in the scientific community, and it has helped many researchers, including myself, to better understand these mysterious objects. Black holes are not just empty voids; they are regions of space where gravity is so strong that nothing, not even light, can escape from them. This makes them incredibly intriguing and a topic of ongoing research. Scientists continue to explore the nature of black holes, their formation, and their role in the universe. Understanding black holes can also help us learn more about the fundamental laws of physics and the structure of space-time itself. As we dive deeper into this subject, we uncover more about the universe and our place within it, making the study of black holes an exciting frontier in modern science.\nContext recap: Chapter 4 - Fourth Lecture: Understanding Black Holes\nBefore the year 1970, my research was mainly about general relativity, which is a theory that explains how gravity works in our universe. I was particularly interested in whether there had been a big bang singularity, which is a point in time when the universe began. One evening, shortly after my daughter Lucy was born, I found myself thinking deeply about black holes as I got ready for bed. Because of my disability, this process took me a bit longer, which gave me plenty of time to reflect on these fascinating cosmic phenomena.\nWhy this matters: Chapter 4 helps learners in Physics/Cosmology connect ideas from Illustrated Theory of Everything to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
